sql:
SELECT p.title, p.acceptance_rate, p.frequency
FROM problems p
WHERE p.acceptance_rate > (
  SELECT AVG(acceptance_rate)
  FROM problems
) AND p.frequency < (
  SELECT MAX(frequency)
  FROM problems
);

SELECT forum_posts.post_content
FROM forum_posts
INNER JOIN comments ON forum_posts.post_id = comments.post_id
WHERE comments.likes_count > (
  SELECT AVG(likes_count) FROM comments
);

external_knowledge:
Highly respected users: Users with a reputation score greater than 1000; 
Experts: Users at the 'Expert' level with over 100 submissions and an acceptance rate above 0.5; 
Tackle harder problems frequently: Problems with a difficulty of 'Hard', an acceptance rate above 0.8, and a frequency over 50; 
Longer names: At least 6 characters.

- 'Really good acceptance rate' refers to problems with an acceptance rate greater than 70%.;
- 'More popularity than usual based on upvotes' means the upvotes count for a problem is above the average number of upvotes for all problems.;
- 'Attracted the most attention by the number of times it was tackled' refers to the problem that appears most frequently in the submissions dataset. This is determined by ordering the results by the count of problem occurrences in submissions in descending order and selecting the top one.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(problem_id) 
FROM problems 
WHERE author_id = (SELECT user_id FROM users ORDER BY reputation_score DESC LIMIT 1);

SELECT * 
FROM problems 
WHERE views_count = (SELECT MAX(views_count) FROM problems);

SELECT p.title, t.tag_name
FROM problems p
LEFT JOIN tags t ON p.problem_id = t.problem_id;
